  "prompt": "What is the formula to calculate a synchronous speed of a motor?",
  "response": "The **synchronous speed** of an AC motor is the speed at which the magnetic field produced by the stator winding rotates. It is determined by the frequency of the AC power supply and the number of poles in the motor. The formula to calculate the synchronous speed (\\(N_s\\)) is:\n\n\\[\nN_s = \\frac{120 \\cdot f}{P}\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\(N_s\\) = synchronous speed in revolutions per minute (RPM),\n- \\(f\\) = frequency of the AC power supply in Hertz (Hz),\n- \\(P\\) = number of poles in the motor.\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **Frequency (\\(f\\))**: Typically 50 Hz or 60 Hz, depending on the region.\n2. **Number of Poles (\\(P\\))**: Determined by the motor's design (e.g., 2-pole, 4-pole, etc.).\n3. The factor \"120\" is a constant derived from the relationship between frequency, poles, and RPM.\n\n### Example:\nFor a 60 Hz, 4-pole motor:\n\\[\nN_s = \\frac{120 \\cdot 60}{4} = 1800 \\text{ RPM}\n\\]",
